General Analysis¶

The COVID-19 dataset from Our World in Data provides a comprehensive global overview of the pandemic since its beginning in early 2020. The dataset covers 7 continents (Asia, Europe, Africa, Oceania, North America, South America, and one unnamed/NaN category) and includes data from 255 countries and territories worldwide. This extensive coverage allows for both global and regional analysis of the pandemic's trajectory.

The dataset tracks multiple metrics including total cases, new cases (with smoothing), and total deaths, providing a multifaceted view of how the pandemic evolved over time across different geographical regions.

df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
global_df = df.groupby("date").agg({
    "total_cases": "sum",
    "total_deaths": "sum",
    "new_cases": "sum"
}).reset_index()
df = df.dropna(subset=['date'])

# Convert date to datetime for proper filtering
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])

# Filter data up to July 1, 2024 early to reduce memory usage
df = df[df['date'] <= '2024-07-01']

# Replace NaN with 0 for numeric columns to prevent aggregation issues
df = df.fillna(0)

# Group data by date and sum up the metrics
global_cases = df.groupby('date')[['total_cases', 'new_cases_smoothed', 'total_deaths']].sum().reset_index()

# Ensure numeric columns are actually numeric
for col in ['total_cases', 'new_cases_smoothed', 'total_deaths']:
    global_cases[col] = pd.to_numeric(global_cases[col], errors='coerce').fillna(0)

# Melt the DataFrame for easier plotting with Plotly Express
df_melted = global_cases.melt(
    id_vars='date', 
    value_vars=['total_cases', 'new_cases_smoothed', 'total_deaths'],
    var_name='Metric', 
    value_name='Count'
)

# Create an interactive line plot with a logarithmic y-axis
fig = px.line(
    df_melted, 
    x='date', 
    y='Count', 
    color='Metric',
    title='Global COVID-19 Trends Over Time',
    labels={'date': 'Date', 'Count': 'Count (Millions)', 'Metric': 'COVID Metrics'}
)

# Update the layout: set log scale on y-axis and choose an aesthetic theme
fig.update_yaxes(type='log')

# Simplified layout configuration to reduce complexity
fig.update_layout(
    template='seaborn',
    width=900,
    height=500,
    margin=dict(l=40, r=40, t=80, b=40),
    xaxis_title="Date",
    yaxis_title="Count",
    legend_title_text='COVID Metrics',
    xaxis=dict(
        rangeselector=dict(
            buttons=list([
                dict(count=1, label="1m", step="month", stepmode="backward"),
                dict(count=6, label="6m", step="month", stepmode="backward"),
                dict(count=1, label="YTD", step="year", stepmode="todate"),
                dict(count=1, label="1y", step="year", stepmode="backward"),
                dict(step="all")
            ])
        ),
        rangeslider=dict(visible=True),
        type="date"
    )
)

# Display the figure
fig.show()

Global COVID-19 Trends Over Time¶

The time series visualization shows the progression of COVID-19 from January 2020 through July 2024 using a logarithmic scale to accommodate the wide range of values:

  • Total Cases (Blue Line): The cumulative case count shows rapid growth in early 2020, followed by a more gradual increase that appears to plateau around 700-750 million cases globally by 2024. This differs from the 3.2 billion figure mentioned, which appears to be an error.

  • New Cases (Red Line): This metric reveals multiple distinct waves of infection throughout the pandemic. Notable peaks occurred in early 2021, early 2022, and a significant spike in early 2023. After this last major wave, new cases have substantially declined to lower levels through 2023-2024.

  • Total Deaths (Green Line): The global death toll appears to have plateaued at approximately 7-8 million deaths. The death curve shows a pattern of rapid increase in 2020 followed by a more gradual rise that stabilized in late 2022.

The visualization illustrates how the relationship between cases and deaths changed over time, likely reflecting improvements in treatment protocols, vaccination campaigns, and possibly virus mutations affecting virulence.

Continental Distribution of COVID-19 Cases¶

The pie chart reveals the uneven global distribution of reported COVID-19 cases:

  • Asia: Leads with 35.2% of global cases, aligning with its position as the world's most populous continent.

  • Europe: Accounts for 33.1% of cases, despite having a smaller population than Asia, suggesting higher case reporting, testing capacity, or actual infection rates.

  • North America: Represents 17.8% of global cases, with a significant portion likely coming from the United States.

  • South America: Contributed 10.3% of total cases, reflecting substantial outbreaks in countries like Brazil.

  • Africa: Despite being the second-most populous continent, Africa accounts for only 2.04% of reported cases, likely indicating significant underreporting due to limited testing infrastructure rather than a true lower incidence.

  • Oceania: Reports the smallest share at 1.62%, reflecting both smaller population size and potentially more effective containment measures in countries like Australia and New Zealand.

This continental distribution highlights how testing capacity, reporting systems, population size, and public health responses all influenced the recorded impact of COVID-19 across different regions.

The actual global burden of COVID-19 is likely higher than these reported figures due to limitations in testing capacity, reporting mechanisms, and differences in case definitions across countries.

Hypothesis-1¶

Countries with longer life expectancies, higher human development indexes, and lower smoking rates among both men and women will experience lower COVID-19 case fatality ratios and better overall outcomes.¶

The reasoning behind this hypothesis is that higher life expectancy and HDI generally indicate robust healthcare infrastructures, effective public health policies, and healthier lifestyle practices. In contrast, lower smoking rates reduce respiratory vulnerabilities, making populations more resilient to severe COVID-19 impacts. Together, these factors are expected to contribute to a reduced case fatality ratio.

Procedure¶

  • To test this hypothesis, we first ensured that key variables—such as life expectancy, HDI, and smoking prevalence—had no missing values by replacing any missing entries with zeros. We then calculated the case fatality ratio (CFR) by dividing total deaths by total cases. After grouping the data by country and filtering out rows with zero values for critical metrics, we created scatter plots with regression lines to visually inspect the relationships between CFR and each variable (life expectancy, HDI, female smokers, and male smokers).

  • The Case Fatality Ratio (CFR) is calculated as:

    $CFR = \frac{Total\ Deaths}{Total\ Cases}$

    This gives a proportion, which can be multiplied by 100 to express it as a percentage if desired.

Results¶

df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
df['male_smokers'] = df['male_smokers'].fillna(0)

df['case_fatality_ratio'] = df['case_fatality_ratio'].fillna(0)

Hypothesis-2¶

Countries with higher cardiovascular death rates and greater diabetes prevalence will experience worse COVID-19 outcomes, meaning they will have higher case fatality ratios.¶

This hypothesis is based on the understanding that both cardiovascular diseases and diabetes are major risk factors for severe COVID-19 complications. In countries where these comorbidities are more common, the overall population may be more vulnerable to the virus. Consequently, when a larger proportion of the population suffers from these conditions, the likelihood of severe outcomes—including higher mortality rates—rises, resulting in a higher case fatality ratio (CFR).

The CFR is calculated using the formula:

$ CFR = \frac{Total\ Deaths}{Total\ Cases}$

​ This ratio provides an estimate of the severity of the disease by comparing the number of deaths to the number of confirmed cases.

Procedure¶

  • To test this hypothesis, we first ensured that key variables—such as cardiovascular death rates and diabetes prevalence—had no missing values by replacing any missing entries with zeros. We then calculated the case fatality ratio (CFR) by dividing total deaths by total cases. After grouping the data by country and filtering out rows with zero values for critical metrics, we created scatter plots with regression lines to visually inspect the relationships between CFR and each variable (cardiovascular deaths and diabetes prevalence).
Results¶

Hypothesis-3¶

In countries with limited COVID-19 testing and weaker healthcare systems, the actual number of pandemic-related deaths is likely much higher than officially reported. This discrepancy is evident when excess mortality significantly surpasses the reported COVID-19 death counts.¶

In regions with constrained healthcare infrastructure and insufficient testing capabilities, many COVID-19 cases and deaths may go undiagnosed and unreported. Factors contributing to this underreporting include:​

  • Limited Testing Capacity: Without widespread testing, many infections remain undetected, leading to undercounted cases and deaths.​

  • Overburdened Healthcare Systems: Healthcare facilities overwhelmed by patient loads may not accurately record all COVID-19-related fatalities.​

  • Inadequate Death Registration Systems: Some countries lack robust systems for recording and classifying deaths, resulting in incomplete data.​

Excess mortality serves as a more comprehensive metric, capturing both direct and indirect deaths related to the pandemic, including those not officially attributed to COVID-19. Studies have highlighted significant underestimations in official COVID-19 death statistics, particularly in countries with limited testing and healthcare resources

Procedure¶

​To investigate whether countries with lower testing rates and weaker healthcare infrastructures have significantly higher excess mortality compared to reported COVID-19 deaths—suggesting underreporting—we conducted a comprehensive analysis. We utilized a dataset containing information on total deaths, excess mortality, testing rates, and hospital bed availability per country. By calculating the underreporting ratio (excess mortality divided by reported deaths) and normalizing the data for comparability, we created a scatter plot visualization. This chart plots testing rates against hospital bed availability, with bubble size and color indicating the underreporting ratio.

Results¶

In [17]:
df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv", parse_dates=["date"])
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
df_country = df.sort_values('date').groupby('location').last().reset_index()
required_cols = ['total_deaths', 'excess_mortality_cumulative_absolute', 
                 'total_tests_per_thousand', 'hospital_beds_per_thousand']
df_country = df_country.dropna(subset=required_cols)
df_country = df_country[df_country['total_deaths'] > 0]
df_country.loc[:, 'underreporting_ratio'] = abs(df_country['excess_mortality_cumulative_absolute'] / 
                                             df_country['total_deaths'])
df_plot = df_country[['location', 'underreporting_ratio', 'total_tests_per_thousand', 'hospital_beds_per_thousand']].copy()
def normalize_series(s):
    return 10 * (s - s.min()) / (s.max() - s.min())

for col in ['underreporting_ratio', 'total_tests_per_thousand', 'hospital_beds_per_thousand']:
    df_plot.loc[:, col] = normalize_series(df_plot[col])
df_plot = df_plot.sort_values('location')

fig_bubble = px.scatter(
    df_plot,
    x="total_tests_per_thousand",
    y="hospital_beds_per_thousand",
    size="underreporting_ratio",
    color="underreporting_ratio",
    hover_name="location",
    size_max=40,
    title="Scatter plot: Testing vs. Hospital Beds",
    labels={
        "total_tests_per_thousand": "Tests per Thousand",
        "hospital_beds_per_thousand": "Hospital Beds per Thousand ",
        "underreporting_ratio": "Underreporting Ratio"
    },
    color_continuous_scale=px.colors.sequential.RdBu
)
fig_bubble.show()
  1. Hypothesis-4¶

Countries that invest in robust healthcare infrastructure—reflected by higher hospital beds per thousand—tend to experience lower rates of hospitalization and ICU admissions relative to the number of new COVID-19 cases¶

A strong healthcare infrastructure can enable:

  • Early and effective intervention: Better-equipped hospitals allow for prompt treatment, which can prevent cases from escalating to severe levels.

  • Improved outpatient care: Sufficient hospital capacity often goes hand-in-hand with robust outpatient services that manage cases before hospitalization becomes necessary.

  • Efficient resource allocation: More hospital beds per capita generally indicate more comprehensive healthcare systems, which can quickly adapt to surges in cases and prevent overload.

These factors contribute to reducing both the hospitalization and ICU rates, supporting the idea that countries with more hospital beds per thousand are better prepared to manage patient loads during a health crisis.

Procedure¶

We grouped the dataset by country—selecting the most recent record for each—to ensure current representation, and defined two key metrics:

  1. $Hospitalization rate = \frac{hospitalizations\ per\ million}{new\ cases\ smoothed\ per\ million}.$

  2. $ICU rate = \frac{icu\ admissions\ per\ million}{new\ cases\ smoothed\ per\ million}.$

These formulas normalize the number of hospitalizations and ICU admissions by new case counts, enabling fair cross-country comparisons and serving as indicators of healthcare response, where lower rates suggest a more effective system in managing COVID-19 without overwhelming hospital resources.

Hypothesis-5¶

Regions with higher population density tend to experience a faster and wider spread of COVID-19. This is reflected in the higher average rate of new COVID-19 cases per million inhabitants.¶

In densely populated regions, people are more likely to be in close proximity to one another, which facilitates the transmission of contagious diseases such as COVID-19. The increased rate of interaction and contact raises the probability of virus spread, leading to higher numbers of new cases per million in these areas.

Procedure¶

The analysis started by reading a comprehensive COVID-19 dataset containing 'population_density' and 'new_cases_per_million' among other variables. After cleaning the data by removing rows with missing or zero values and eliminating extreme outliers (cap values at the 99th percentile), the data was aggregated per country. Average new cases per million were computed and countries were grouped into density groups using 'pd.qcut', merging the lower two quartiles (Low and Mid-Low) into a single "Low-Mid" group. The Pearson ANOVA F-test was then applied, using the F-statistic formula:

$ F = \frac{\text{Between-group variance}}{\text{Within-group variance}} $

This statistical test was used to check if the differences in average new case rates between the density groups are significant.

Results¶

Hypothesis-6¶

Countries that have a higher overall median age or a larger proportion of individuals aged 65 and older tend to have higher rates of COVID-19 deaths per million inhabitants.¶

Older populations are generally more vulnerable to severe outcomes when infected with COVID-19 because aging is often accompanied by weakened immune responses and a higher likelihood of pre-existing health conditions. As a result, countries with higher median ages or a greater percentage of citizens over 65 can be expected to show elevated death rates during the pandemic. This expectation is supported by epidemiological evidence indicating that age is a major risk factor for COVID-19 mortality.

Procedure¶

The analysis began by importing a comprehensive COVID-19 dataset containing various metrics, including the median age of each country’s population, the percentage of the population aged 65 and older, and total deaths per million. The steps were:

  • Aggregation:
    For each country, the data was grouped to retain the first observation for median_age and aged_65_older while taking the maximum value of total_deaths_per_million, ensuring the latest and most representative data per country was used.

  • Correlation Analysis:
    The Pearson correlation coefficient was computed using the formula
    $ r = \frac{\text{Cov}(X, Y)}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y} $
    where $\text{Cov}(X, Y)$ is the covariance between the predictor (median age or percentage aged 65+) and the response (COVID-19 deaths per million). Along with the correlation coefficients, p-values were obtained to assess the significance of these relationships.

  • Visualization:
    Regression plots were generated using seaborn’s regplot to visualize the relationship between the predictors (median age and % aged 65+) and the outcome (deaths per million).

Results¶

Hypothesis-7¶

Countries with greater healthcare resources, particularly more hospital beds per capita, tend to have lower COVID-19 mortality rates.​¶

The availability of hospital beds is a critical component of healthcare infrastructure. During the COVID-19 pandemic, sufficient hospital bed capacity allowed for timely treatment of patients, reducing the likelihood of severe outcomes and deaths. Conversely, limited bed availability can lead to overwhelmed healthcare systems, delayed care, and increased mortality.

Procedure¶

The methodology for analyzing the relationship between healthcare infrastructure and COVID-19 mortality rates involved several key steps:​

  • Metric Computation:

$ Deaths\ per\ Case\ Percentage= \frac{Cumulative\ Deaths\ per\ Million}{Cumulative\ Cases\ per\ Million} \times 100 $

This metric provides insight into the severity and fatality of the disease within each country.

  • Grouping by Healthcare Capacity: Countries were categorized into three groups—Low, Medium, and High—based on 'hospital_beds_per_thousand' using quantile-based discretization. This stratification allowed for comparative analysis across different levels of healthcare infrastructure.​

  • Temporal Analysis: The average 'deaths_per_case_pct' was computed for each group over time, starting from June 8, 2020. To minimize daily fluctuations and observe broader trends, the data was downsampled to every 10th day.

Results¶

In [26]:
df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv", parse_dates=["date"])

# Step 1: Data Cleaning & Preprocessing
# --------------------------------------------------
cols = ['location', 'date', 'hospital_beds_per_thousand', 
        'new_deaths_per_million', 'new_cases_per_million']
df_filtered = df[cols].copy()
df_filtered.dropna(subset=cols, inplace=True)

df_filtered['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_filtered['date'])
df_filtered = df_filtered.sort_values(['location', 'date'])
df_filtered = df_filtered[df_filtered['new_cases_per_million'] > 0]

# Step 2: Compute Static and Cumulative Metrics
# --------------------------------------------------
df_filtered['beds'] = df_filtered.groupby('location')['hospital_beds_per_thousand'].transform('first')
df_filtered['cum_deaths_per_million'] = df_filtered.groupby('location')['new_deaths_per_million'].cumsum()
df_filtered['cum_cases_per_million'] = df_filtered.groupby('location')['new_cases_per_million'].cumsum()
df_filtered = df_filtered[df_filtered['cum_cases_per_million'] > 0]
df_filtered['deaths_per_case_pct'] = (df_filtered['cum_deaths_per_million'] / df_filtered['cum_cases_per_million']) * 100

# Step 3: Grouping by Hospital Bed Capacity (3 categories)
# --------------------------------------------------
df_filtered['bed_group'] = pd.qcut(df_filtered['beds'], q=3, labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"])

# Step 4: Prepare Data for Cumulative Animated Plot
# --------------------------------------------------
grouped = df_filtered.groupby(['date', 'bed_group'])['deaths_per_case_pct'].mean().reset_index()

# Downsample and filter from 2020-06-08 onwards
grouped = grouped[(grouped['date'].dt.dayofyear % 10 == 0) & (grouped['date'] >= '2020-06-08')].copy()
grouped['date_str'] = grouped['date'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
grouped['bed_group'] = pd.Categorical(grouped['bed_group'], categories=["Low", "Medium", "High"], ordered=True)

# Step 5: Create Animated Bar Chart
# --------------------------------------------------
fig = px.bar(
    grouped,
    x='bed_group',
    y='deaths_per_case_pct',
    color='bed_group',
    animation_frame='date_str',
    animation_group='bed_group',
    range_y=[0, 5],  # max y-axis = 5%
    title="Cumulative COVID-19 Deaths per Reported Case (%) by Hospital Bed Group Over Time",
    labels={
        "bed_group": "Hospital Bed Group",
        "deaths_per_case_pct": "Cumulative Deaths per Case (%)"
    }
)

fig.update_layout(
    showlegend=False,
    xaxis_title="Hospital Bed Group",
    yaxis_title="Cumulative Deaths per Case (%)",
    transition=dict(duration=300, easing='cubic-in-out')
)

fig.show()

Hypothesis-9¶

Countries with higher booster vaccination coverage (measured as total_boosters_per_hundred) are expected to have lower hospitalization and ICU admission rates relative to new COVID-19 cases.¶

Booster doses help sustain and enhance immunity over time, reducing the severity of COVID-19 infections. This maintained immunity should lead to fewer severe cases that require hospitalization or intensive care, ultimately lowering the rates of hospital and ICU admissions relative to the number of new cases.

Procedure¶

The analysis involves first calculating two key ratios: the hospitalization rate, defined as the number of hospitalized patients per million divided by new cases (smoothed per million), and the ICU rate, defined as the number of ICU patients per million divided by new cases (smoothed per million). Next, these ratios are compared across countries against their booster vaccination coverage (total_boosters_per_hundred) using regression plots and correlation analysis.

Results¶

df_latest = df_filtered.sort_values('date').groupby('location').last().reset_index()

# Compute the derived metrics:
# Hospitalization Rate = hosp_patients_per_million / new_cases_smoothed_per_million
# ICU Rate = icu_patients_per_million / new_cases_smoothed_per_million
df_latest['hospitalization_rate'] = df_latest['hosp_patients_per_million'] / df_latest['new_cases_smoothed_per_million']
df_latest['icu_rate'] = df_latest['icu_patients_per_million'] / df_latest['new_cases_smoothed_per_million']

# Plotting: Create scatter plots with regression lines to visualize relationships
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))

# Scatter plot for Booster Coverage vs Hospitalization Rate
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.regplot(
    data=df_latest,
    x='total_boosters_per_hundred',
    y='hospitalization_rate',
    scatter_kws={'s': 50, 'alpha': 0.7},
    line_kws={'color': 'red', 'lw': 2}
)
plt.title('Booster Vaccination vs Hospitalization Rate')
plt.xlabel('Total Boosters per Hundred')
plt.ylabel('Hospitalization Rate (Hosp Patients / New Cases Smoothed per Million)')
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)

# Scatter plot for Booster Coverage vs ICU Rate
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
sns.regplot(
    data=df_latest,
    x='total_boosters_per_hundred',
    y='icu_rate',
    scatter_kws={'s': 50, 'alpha': 0.7},
    line_kws={'color': 'blue', 'lw': 2}
)
plt.title('Booster Vaccination vs ICU Rate')
plt.xlabel('Total Boosters per Hundred')
plt.ylabel('ICU Rate (ICU Patients / New Cases Smoothed per Million)')
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Optionally, print correlation coefficients for additional insight
corr_hosp = df_latest[['total_boosters_per_hundred', 'hospitalization_rate']].corr().iloc[0, 1]
corr_icu = df_latest[['total_boosters_per_hundred', 'icu_rate']].corr().iloc[0, 1]
print(f"Correlation between boosters and hospitalization rate: {corr_hosp:.2f}")
print(f"Correlation between boosters and ICU rate: {corr_icu:.2f}")

Correlation between boosters and hospitalization rate: 0.19
Correlation between boosters and ICU rate: 0.03
  1. Regression Plot Analysis:

    • Both regression plots show a positive relationship between booster vaccination coverage and the derived rates.

    • The correlation between boosters and the hospitalization rate is 0.19, while the correlation between boosters and the ICU rate is 0.03.

These results indicate that, contrary to the initial expectation, the data shows a slight positive association rather than the expected negative association.

Conclusion¶

Although the hypothesis predicted that higher booster coverage would correlate with lower hospitalization and ICU rates, the analysis reveals a weak positive relationship. This suggests that other factors might be influencing the severity outcomes, or that the effect of booster coverage on reducing severe cases may be more complex than anticipated. Further investigation and additional variables might be necessary to fully understand the relationship between booster vaccinations and severe COVID-19 outcomes.

Hypothesis-10¶

Higher vaccination coverage at the continent level is expected to be associated with lower COVID-19 reproduction rates over time. This means that as more people get vaccinated, the virus should spread less rapidly.¶

Vaccines are designed to reduce both the severity of infections and the likelihood of virus transmission. As vaccination coverage increases, more individuals develop immunity, leading to fewer opportunities for the virus to spread. However, occasional increases in reproduction rates may indicate the emergence of new, more transmissible variants that temporarily overcome vaccine-induced immunity.

Procedure¶

First, the dataset was filtered to include key variables such as total vaccinations per hundred and reproduction rate, along with continent information. The data was then aggregated by continent and date to compute the average vaccination coverage and reproduction rate for each region. An animated scatter plot was created where each continent is represented as a “balloon” that moves over time. The x-axis shows the average vaccination coverage, the y-axis shows the average reproduction rate, and the balloon size is proportional to the reproduction rate.

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Load the dataset and parse dates
df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv", parse_dates=["date"])

# Select relevant columns for analysis
cols = ['location', 'date', 'total_vaccinations_per_hundred', 'reproduction_rate', 'continent']
df_vacc = df[cols].copy()

# Drop rows with missing values for vaccination or reproduction rate
df_vacc.dropna(subset=['total_vaccinations_per_hundred', 'reproduction_rate'], inplace=True)

# Optionally, filter out records with non-positive vaccination values
df_vacc = df_vacc[df_vacc['total_vaccinations_per_hundred'] > 0]
df_vacc = df_vacc[df_vacc['reproduction_rate'] > 0]
df_vacc['reproduction_rate'] = df_vacc['reproduction_rate']*100
# Create a string version of the date for animation purposes
df_vacc['date_str'] = df_vacc['date'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

# Create an animated scatter plot
fig = px.scatter(
    df_vacc, 
    x='total_vaccinations_per_hundred', 
    y='reproduction_rate', 
    animation_frame='date_str',
    animation_group='continent',
    color='continent',
    size='reproduction_rate',
    hover_name='location',
    size_max=20,
    range_x=[0, df_vacc['total_vaccinations_per_hundred'].max() + 10],
    range_y=[0, df_vacc['reproduction_rate'].max() + 1],
    title='Dynamic Scatter Plot: Vaccination Coverage vs. Reproduction Rate'
)

# Update axis titles for clarity
fig.update_layout(
    xaxis_title='Total Vaccinations per Hundred',
    yaxis_title='Reproduction Rate'
)

fig.show()

  1. Scatter Plot Analysis:

    • The animated scatter plot shows that, as time passes, the sizes of the continent balloons generally decrease, indicating a drop in reproduction rates as vaccination coverage improves. However, there are instances where the balloon size increases, which could suggest the appearance of new COVID-19 variants that temporarily raise the reproduction rate despite high vaccination coverage.

Conclusion¶

The analysis supports the notion that increased vaccination coverage correlates with a reduction in COVID-19 transmission at the continent level. While the overall trend shows a decrease in reproduction rates over time, occasional spikes in balloon size highlight the potential impact of emerging variants, emphasizing the need for continued vigilance and possible vaccine updates.
